[[Lieutenant-General]] '''Sir Herbert Taylor''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|GCB|GCH}} (29 September 1775 – 20 March 1839) was the first Private Secretary to the Sovereign of the [[United Kingdom]], serving Kings George III, George IV and William IV.

==Military career==
Taylor was the son of Rev. Edward Taylor of Bifrons, [[Patrixbourne]], Kent and his wife Margaret Payler<ref name=Burke>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qf4GAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA108 John Burke ''A genealogical and heraldic history of the commoners of Great Britain Volume 3'']</ref> daughter of Thomas Turner Payler of Ileden, who died at Brussels in 1780.<ref name=Hasted>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=63564 ''Parishes: Patrixborne'', The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent: Volume 9 (1800), pp. 277–286. Date accessed: 24 November 2010]</ref> He joined the [[2nd Dragoon Guards]] as a [[Cornet (military rank)|cornet]] in 1794.<ref name=odnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/27031 Herbert Taylor at Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> Later that year he was promoted to lieutenant and then the following year to captain.<ref name=odnb/> In 1795 he served as assistant secretary and [[aide de camp]] to the [[Prince Frederick, Duke of York and Albany|Duke of York]], then commander-in-chief of the British Army.<ref name=odnb/> Taylor was later the Duke of York's assistant military secretary, an office he held until 1798.<ref name=odnb/> He was later a Major. In 1798 he was made [[Aide de Camp]], [[Military Secretary (United Kingdom)|Military Secretary]] and [[Private Secretary]] to the [[Charles Cornwallis, 1st Marquess Cornwallis|Marquess Cornwallis]], [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]].<ref name=odnb/> In the following year he returned to the Duke of York's service and remained there until 1805, although he was transferred to the [[9th West Indian Regiment]] as a [[lieutenant-colonel]] in 1801.<ref name=odnb/>

However, in the following year, with a period of relative calm in the midst of the [[Napoleonic Wars]], he was placed on half pay.<ref name=odnb/> In that year he joined the [[Coldstream Guards]], in which he became a brevet colonel in 1810. In 1805 he became private secretary to [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]], and then, from 1811 private secretary to [[Queen Charlotte]], the [[queen consort]].<ref name=odnb/> He retained that office until 1818.

Taylor commanded a brigade at [[Antwerp]] 1813–1814, and was sent on a diplomatic mission to [[Charles XIV John of Sweden|Bernadotte of Sweden]] in 1814.<ref name=odnb/> He was Member of Parliament ([[Member of Parliament|MP]]) for [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]] 1820–23.<ref name=odnb/> From 1820 to 1827 he was [[List of Ambassadors from the United Kingdom to Germany|Ambassador to Berlin]] and then [[Military Secretary (United Kingdom)|Military Secretary]],<ref name=odnb/> having become colonel for life of the [[85th Foot Regiment]] in 1823. He was first and principal aide de camp to [[George IV of the United Kingdom|King George IV]] in 1827, and also deputy [[Secretary at War]].<ref name=odnb/> From 1828 to 1830 he was [[Adjutant-General to the Forces]].<ref name=odnb/> He became private secretary to the new king, [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]], in 1830.<ref name=odnb/> On the death of the king in 1837 he retired, although he was first and principal aide de camp to [[Queen Victoria]] 1837–39.

Taylor became a [[Major-General]] in 1813, and a [[Lieutenant-General]] in 1825. He was [[St Katharine's by the Tower|Master of St Katherine's Hospital]], [[Regent's Park]], and [[Master Surveyor]] and [[Surveyor-General of the Ordnance]]  from 1828. He died in 1839.<ref name=odnb/> The monument to him at St. Katherine's is by the sculptor [[Peter Rouw]].

==Sir Brook Taylor==
Brook Taylor (1776 – 15 October 1846) was Herbert Taylor's younger brother.<ref name="odnb"/> Brook Taylor joined the diplomatic service and was British [[Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary|minister]] to [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel|Hesse-Cassel]] and [[Electorate of Cologne|Cologne]] 1801–06,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=15336 |date=10 February 1801 |startpage=174}}</ref> to [[Kingdom of Denmark|Denmark]] in 1807, to [[Kingdom of Württemberg|Württemberg]] 1814–20,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=16915 |date=9 July 1814 |startpage=1389}}</ref> to [[Kingdom of Bavaria|Bavaria]] 1820–28 and to [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] 1828–31.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=18427 |date=28 December 1827 |startpage=2644}}</ref> He was knighted GCH in 1822, and was admitted to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1829.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=18620 |date=16 October 1829 |startpage=1893}}</ref> He deputised for Sir Herbert during the latter's absences from the court.<ref>[http://www.historyhome.co.uk/people/taylor-b.htm Sir Brook Taylor (1776-1846)], historyhome</ref>

